docs.abstract: Only sweeping clemency will address the systemic injustice players like us have been protesting.
docs.snippet: Only sweeping clemency will address the systemic injustice players like us have been protesting.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump recently made an offer to National Football League players like us who are committed to protesting injustice. Instead of protesting, he suggested, we should give him names of people we believe were “unfairly treated by the justice system.” If he agrees they were treated unfairly, he said, he will pardon them.

headline.main: N.F.L. Players to Trump: Here’s Whom You Should Pardon

docs.abstract: Trump is using the pardoning of black people as marketing tactic rather than statement of principle.
docs.snippet: Trump is using the pardoning of black people as marketing tactic rather than statement of principle.
docs.lead_paragraph: Last week Donald Trump proposed pardoning Muhammad Ali, even though Ali’s conviction for refusing to be drafted into the Vietnam War had been already overturned.

docs.abstract: In these anxious times, Mr. Cave thinks we all need a place to unfurl. He has turned the Park Avenue Armory into a giant dance floor for “The Let Go.”
docs.snippet: In these anxious times, Mr. Cave thinks we all need a place to unfurl. He has turned the Park Avenue Armory into a giant dance floor for “The Let Go.”
docs.lead_paragraph: The “Soul Train” line appeared out of nowhere, fully formed, like it was meant to be. At the Park Avenue Armory on Wednesday night, dozens of dancers paired off to spin and bounce, sashaying between 40-foot-high glittering curtains.

headline.main: Nick Cave Wants You to Work It Out on the Dance Floor

docs.abstract: In a new exhibition in London, Yinka Shonibare has collected works that challenge the resurgence of extreme right-wing politics and xenophobia.
docs.snippet: In a new exhibition in London, Yinka Shonibare has collected works that challenge the resurgence of extreme right-wing politics and xenophobia.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Can political art be beautiful? Can beauty itself be a form of resistance? These are some of the questions posed by the British-Nigerian artist Yinka Shonibare in a new exhibition he has curated at Stephen Friedman Gallery in London.

headline.main: It’s Time for African Resistance, This Artist Says

docs.abstract: The birds come, the birds go. All that changes is the pecking order.
docs.snippet: The birds come, the birds go. All that changes is the pecking order.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Global Big Day last month, birders around the world counted all the species they could spot in 24 hours. It was a super-birding event in the bonanza that is spring migration — which runs from late April to early June, but peaks for songbirds in May — when millions of birds make their way from parts south to breed in the Northern latitudes.

headline.main: Young Urban Birders, Open Your Hearts to the Treetops!
